{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Cache keys generated from identical query parameters are always identical, and keys from different parameters never collide.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a deterministic key-derivation boundary. Real failures are in normalization/serialization/hash logic and can be exposed by direct inputs to the key generator without I/O.","test_description":"Call the key-generation function/object directly with parameter sets that differ by ordering, typing, and value. Assert identical canonical inputs produce identical keys and a large adversarial corpus of distinct inputs produces no duplicates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.86,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The TTL for a cache entry is computed correctly based on the data category's configured freshness rule (e.g., user profiles = 5 minutes, product catalog = 1 hour).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"TTL computation is deterministic rule evaluation from category/config input to duration output. No real infra is required to reproduce the failure boundary.","test_description":"Invoke the TTL calculator with an in-memory freshness-rule config and categories (including unknown/misconfigured categories). Assert exact TTL outputs and fallback/error behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A pure mock of strategy selection can miss wiring failures between memory monitor, config, and policy switcher. The minimum realistic boundary is modules wired together with controlled memory readings.","test_description":"Run cache manager + strategy selector + config loader together. Feed memory-usage readings just below/at/above threshold and assert active policy transitions LRU->LFU only when configured conditions are met.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.31,"Integration":0.61,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This depends on DB-write-to-invalidation wiring. In-process mocks can hide trigger/listener/query-mapping bugs. A local PostgreSQL-backed integration test is sufficient; no broader system infra is required.","test_description":"With a real local PostgreSQL test DB and real cache invalidation path, prefill cache entries for multiple rows, execute INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE on target rows, then assert only keys mapped to affected rows are invalidated.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.73,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Algorithm correctness can be unit-tested, but real failures often come from interaction between access tracking and storage operations. Wiring policy + cache state is the minimum robust boundary.","test_description":"Instantiate the real cache with bounded capacity and each policy mode. Perform a sequence of puts/gets that creates distinct recency/frequency rankings, exceed capacity, and assert evicted keys match expected LRU/LFU victims.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.38,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
